<Base title="Layer Your Verification — Augmented Engineering">
  <PatternPage number="2" title="Layer Your Verification" subtitle="V&V became cheap enough to use routinely. Each layer catches what the others miss.">

    <div class="illustration-wrap">
      <IllustrationLayers />
    </div>

    <p>The pattern is simple: <strong>agent generates &rarr; agent reviews &rarr; agent validates &rarr; engineer decides.</strong> Each layer catches what the others miss. Independent verification and validation (IV&V) has existed in systems engineering since the 1970s — mandatory in avionics (DO-178C), medical devices (IEC 62304), and nuclear systems. In most other engineering, it's been too expensive: dedicated V&V teams, parallel review infrastructure, months of effort.</p>

    <p>AI agents change the economics. You can now run three, four, five verification passes for the cost of minutes of compute time. This doesn't change the principle (V&V works). It changes the practice (V&V is accessible to everyday engineering, not just safety-critical projects with dedicated budgets).</p>

    <h2>Where This Applies Across the V-Model</h2>

    <p>Layered verification isn't limited to detailed design. Practitioners are applying it at every phase of product development:</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>V-Model Phase</th><th>What Agents Verify</th><th>Source Evidence</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Requirements</td><td>Consistency checks, testability analysis, conflict detection</td><td>vmodel.eu (93.8% agreement)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Architecture</td><td>Interface checks, performance estimation, verification workflows</td><td>OPAL (recursive V&V)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Detailed Design</td><td>Equation reproduction, safety analysis, manufacturability</td><td>Driven Pendulum (3 errors found)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Testing</td><td>Coverage checks, test case generation, log mining</td><td>vmodel.eu, OPAL</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Documentation</td><td>Claim-evidence tracing, confidence calibration, compliance</td><td>agent-ready-papers (100% coverage)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>The same feedback loop — generate, review, validate, decide — works at each phase. What changes is what you're verifying and which agents are specialized for the task.</p>

    <h2>The Evidence: OPAL Design Review</h2>

    <p>A mixed-signal PCB design for a confocal optical instrument. Class 3B laser, five voltage domains, millivolt-level signals. The review generated 725 checklist items across 14 engineering disciplines, classified by risk (P0 safety-critical, P1 design-influencing, P2 best-practice), then verified in layers.</p>

    <div class="evidence-box">
      <p><strong>The critical finding:</strong> Stopping after the first verification pass would have left 8 of 10 defects undiscovered.</p>
    </div>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Found</th><th>Would have been missed</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>P0 verification</td><td>Laser boot hazard, LDO undersized</td><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><td>V&V audit</td><td>Motor driver logic pin missing</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
        <tr><td>P1 spot-check</td><td>ADC timing, PWM safety regression, thermal</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Full P1</td><td>Reference impedance, DAC init, firmware safety</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
        <tr><td>+ local datasheets</td><td>Voltage drop, 10x resistance error</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>The most concerning defect: FIX-06, where an ESP32 PWM resolution limit caused the safety voltage cap from a previous fix to silently map to 4.1V instead of 2.0V. A safety regression hidden inside an apparent safety fix — found only by the third verification layer.</p>

    <h2>The Recursive Step</h2>

    <p>After the first verification pass appeared clean, the engineer asked: <em>"Can we trust our verifiers?"</em> Three parallel audit agents independently checked the verification results. This recursive step — auditing the auditors — discovered a critical defect (motor driver logic supply pin entirely missing from the schematic) that the primary verification had overlooked.</p>

    <p>This is the same principle behind IV&V in safety-critical systems. What's new is the economics: the recursive check cost minutes, not months.</p>

    <div class="monday-box">
      <h3>Try This Monday</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>After your AI generates output, don't review it yourself — have a second AI pass review it with different instructions</li>
        <li>After that review, ask: "what might both passes have missed?" Run a third pass focused specifically on that question</li>
        <li>Classify your items by risk. Spend thorough verification on the high-consequence items. Spot-check the rest.</li>
        <li>The marginal cost of each additional layer is minutes. The marginal benefit is unpredictable but occasionally critical. Err on the side of one more layer.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="caveat-box">
      <h3>Honest Limitations</h3>
      <p>This evidence comes from one design review of one instrument. "8 of 10 missed by single-pass" is specific to this design — it demonstrates the principle but doesn't quantify a general rate. We don't know the false positive rate across layers, or the precise cost-benefit curve. The open question: when does the nth layer stop finding defects? More data from diverse projects is needed.</p>
    </div>

  </PatternPage>
